**Law 2: The Wreath Product Law**

**Statement.** The Galois group of the vacuum minimal polynomial at each
level has wreath product structure:

*Gal(f₂ₙ/ℚ) ≅ C₂ ≀ C_m, where m = φ(2n−1)/2*

**2.1 Structural Derivation**

The proof has two parts: identifying the C_m factor (outer action) and
the C₂ factors (inner action).

***Part A: The outer C_m factor***

The totally real subfield ℚ(cos(2π/(2n−1))) has Galois group C_m =
C\_{φ(2n−1)/2} over ℚ. This group permutes the m conjugate sector-pairs.
Each sector corresponds to a pair of Z₂ₙ₋₁-characters {ρₖ, ρ₂ₙ₋₁₋ₖ} that
are complex conjugates of each other. The Galois action on
cos(2πk/(2n−1)) permutes these pairs cyclically (when 2n−1 is prime, C_m
is cyclic).

***Part B: The inner C₂ factors***

Within each sector-pair, the orbit-folded 2×2 matrix Fᵣ produces a
quadratic equation over ℚ(cos(2π/(2n−1))). The two roots of this
quadratic are exchanged by a C₂ action. Critically, this C₂ acts
independently on each sector-pair: swapping the roots in one sector does
not affect the others.

***Part C: The wreath product structure***

The full Galois group is generated by: (1) the C_m permuting
sector-pairs, and (2) m independent C₂ factors, one per sector-pair. The
C_m acts on the C₂ factors by permuting them. This is exactly the wreath
product structure:

*C₂ ≀ C_m = (C₂)ᵐ ⋊ C_m*

with order \|Gal\| = 2ᵐ · m.

