**3.3 Full Discriminant Factorizations**

The complete discriminant factorizations reveal both even-exponent
(Galois-neutral) and odd-exponent (Galois-active) primes:

**K₈:** Δ = 2³⁶ × 7⁴ × 43 × 421². Square-free part: 43. The prime 7 =
2n−1 appears but to even power (neutral). The prime 421 appears to even
power (neutral). Only 43 is Galois-active.

**K₁₂:** Δ = 2¹⁹⁰ × 11⁸ × 23 × 353 × 439² × 64217² × 478838249².
Square-free part: 23 × 353 = 8119. Both odd-exponent primes satisfy the
congruence.

**K₁₄:** Δ = 2¹⁵⁶ × 5² × 13¹⁰ × 31² × 79 × 5279 × 32941² × 414259² ×
1256726743². Square-free part: 79 × 5279 = 417041. Both satisfy the
congruence.

**3.4 The Heegner Number Observation**

An intriguing additional observation (two data points, not a proved
law): at K₈ and K₁₀, the square-free discriminant primes are Heegner
numbers (43 and 163 respectively). These are primes d such that ℚ(√(−d))
has class number 1. The Heegner prediction was tested at K₁₂ and
falsified: the square-free discriminant 8119 = 23 × 353 is composite and
neither factor is a Heegner number. The congruence law survived; the
Heegner pattern did not.

**Supporting Result: Pairwise Galois Disjointness**

**Statement.** For all pairs (i, j) with i ≠ j among the computed levels
{K₆, K₈, K₁₀, K₁₂, K₁₄}, the number fields are Galois disjoint:

*ℚ(λ_i) ∩ ℚ(λ_j) = ℚ*

**Proof Strategy**

For each pair, disjointness is established by one of two methods:

**Method A (No common subfield):** If one field has no quadratic
subfield (e.g., C₂ ≀ C₃ has no index-2 subgroup), any intersection must
have degree dividing gcd of the two field degrees. When this gcd is 2
and one field lacks a quadratic subfield, the intersection is trivially
ℚ.

**Method B (Distinct quadratic subfields):** When both fields have
quadratic subfields (e.g., K₆ with ℚ(√5) and K₁₂ with ℚ(√8119)), these
are compared directly. Distinct quadratic subfields force
ℚ-intersection.

**Method C (Resultant):** As a computational check, Res(f_i, f_j) ≠ 0 is
verified, confirming no shared roots.

**Compositum Degree**

The compositum of all five fields has maximal degree:

*\[ℚ(λ₆, λ₈, λ₁₀, λ₁₂, λ₁₄) : ℚ\] = 2 × 6 × 6 × 10 × 12 = 8,640*

No collapse from any pair. Each level of the spectral extractor chain
produces algebraic content with zero overlap with all previous levels.

